<html ng-app="econGraphsApp">
<% include header.ejs %>
<body>
<% include navbar.ejs %>
<div class="container-fluid mainPage" ng-controller="Controller">
	<div class="row">
		<div class="col-md-9">
			<div class="row">
				<div class="col-md-6">
					<h4 class="text-center">Individual Demand</h4>
					<hr/>
					<div id="graph1"></div>
					<div>
						<p>This model assumes that consumers will spend a constant fraction of their income on this good. Specifically, it assumes that consumers' income is ${{ income }}, and that they spend {{alpha}}% of that (or ${{alpha*income/100}}) on this good, regardless of the price.</p>

						<p>At a price of ${{ price }} per unit, therefore, a "representative" individual consumer will choose to buy <i>q<sup>D</sup></i> = ${{alpha*income/100}} / ${{price}} per unit = {{ quantityDemanded*1000/consumers | number : 1}} units.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="col-md-6">
					<h4 class="text-center">Market Supply and Demand</h4>
					<hr/>
					<div id="graph2"></div>
					<div>
						<p>Since there are {{consumers | number:0}} consumers in the market, the total quantity demanded is <i>Q<sup>D</sup></i> = {{ individualQuantityDemanded | number : 1}} units per consumer x {{consumers | number:0}} consumers = {{ shownQuantityDemanded | number : 0 }} units.</p>
						<p>At the same price, producers in this market supply <i>Q<sup>S</sup></i> = {{shownQuantitySupplied | number:0}} units.</p>
							<p ng-if="(price < equilibriumPrice)">
							  	Therefore, this relatively low price results in a <b>shortage</b> (excess demand) of {{ shownQuantityDemanded - shownQuantitySupplied | number:0 }} units.
							</p>
							<p ng-if="(price > equilibriumPrice)">
							    Therefore, this relatively high price results in a <b>surplus</b> (excess supply) of {{ shownQuantitySupplied - shownQuantityDemanded | number:0 }} units.
							</p>
							<p ng-if="(price == equilibriumPrice)">
							    Because the quantity supplied {{ (shownQuantityDemanded == shownQuantitySupplied) ? "equals" : "is just about equal to" }} the quantity demanded in the market, competitive pressures are unlikely to drive the market price up or down; so we say the market is "in equilibrium."
							</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
			
		</div>
		
		<div class="col-md-3">
			<div class="well">
				<p>Price: ${{ price }} per unit<input type="range" min="10" max="50" step="1" ng-model="price"></p>
				<p>Income: ${{ income }}<input type="range" min="100" max="500" step="10" ng-model="income"></p>
				<p>Fraction of income spent on this: {{ alpha }}%<input type="range" min="0" max="100" step="1" ng-model="alpha"></p>
				<p>Number of consumers:  {{ consumers | number:0 }}<input type="range" min="2000" max="5000" step="50" ng-model="consumers"></p>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>
	
	
	
	

</div>
<% include footer.ejs %>
</body>
</html>